detail_description: De Nieuwe Kerk, Rijswijk, also known as the New Church, has a rich history dating back to the 1300s. It is renowned for being the final resting place of William the Silent and several members of the Dutch Royal family. This historic site holds great significance and offers visitors a glimpse into centuries of Dutch heritage and tradition.
name: De Nieuwe Kerk, Rijswijk

excerpt: Still in operation, this famous 17th-century earthenware factory features a museum & guided tours.
detail_description: Royal Delft is a renowned 17th-century earthenware factory that offers guided tours and houses a museum. It is the hub for creating the iconic blue and white patterns on pottery, which are popular throughout the Netherlands. Visitors can witness potters crafting these patterns by hand or using screen printing techniques. The museum showcases some of the oldest examples of Royal Delft pottery and provides insights into its history and Dutch design tradition.
name: Royal Delft

excerpt: Museum on William of Orange & the creation of the Dutch Republic, plus 17th-century arts & crafts.
detail_description: Museum Prinsenhof Delft, once a convent of St. Agatha, holds great historical significance as the former residence of Prince William the Silent, a key figure in the creation of the Dutch Republic. The museum showcases 17th-century arts and crafts alongside exhibits on William's role in the Spanish Revolt. The tragic event that took place here, where William was assassinated by Balthasar Gerard in 1584, is commemorated throughout the museum.
name: Museum Prinsenhof Delft
address: Kantoor & Infopunt:, Sint Agathaplein 1, Sint Agathaplein 4, 2611 HR Delft, Netherlands

excerpt: Delft, a canal-ringed city in the western Netherlands, is known as the manufacturing base for Delftware, hand-painted blue-and-white pottery. In its old town, the medieval Oude Kerk is the burial site of native son and Dutch Master painter Johannes Vermeer. Once the seat of the royal House of Orange, the 15th-century Nieuwe Kerk houses the family's tombs and overlooks Delft's lively market square.
detail_description: Delft, a picturesque city in the western Netherlands, is renowned for its production of Delftware, a distinctive blue-and-white pottery. The charming old town is home to the Oude Kerk, where the famous Dutch Master painter Johannes Vermeer is buried, and the Nieuwe Kerk, which overlooks the bustling market square and houses the tombs of the royal House of Orange. Nearby are Leiden and The Hague, both rich in history and culture.
name: Delft

excerpt: Small museum dedicated to artwork of Johannes Vermeer, with paintings, audio tours & a light studio.
detail_description: The Vermeer Centrum Delft is a small museum located in the heart of Delft, dedicated to showcasing the life and artwork of Johannes Vermeer, a prominent Dutch painter from the Golden Age. Visitors can explore exhibits that provide insight into Vermeer's artistic techniques, influences, and the historical context in which he created his masterpieces. The museum offers audio tours and a light studio experience for an immersive journey through Vermeer's creations.
name: Vermeer Centrum Delft

excerpt: 13th-century church best known for its 75m-tall leaning brick tower & its 9-tonne bell.
detail_description: The Old Church, also known as Oude Kerk, is a 13th-century church located along the banks of the old Oude Delft canal in Delft, Holland. It is renowned for its 75-meter-tall leaning brick tower and a 9-tonne bell. The church has undergone several enlargements and renovations over the years to accommodate a growing number of worshippers.
name: Old Church

detail_description: Beestenmarkt is a charming square located in the heart of Delft city center. It provides a more tranquil atmosphere compared to the bustling Markt square, making it a fantastic alternative for visitors seeking a peaceful experience.
name: Beestenmarkt

detail_description: Delft Windmill de Roos, the only remaining windmill out of 18 that once stood in the city, has been a fixture since 1679. Operated by dedicated volunteers, it produces around 1,500 kilograms of flour weekly from wheat, rye, and spelt. Visitors can climb to the top for a stunning view of Delft and enjoy a warm welcome at the on-site shop and café.
name: Delft Windmill de Roos

excerpt: 1400s city gate & riverside landmark featuring twin Gothic spires & a brick archway.
detail_description: Oostpoort, also known as the Eastern Gate, is a picturesque riverside landmark in Delft that dates back to the 15th and 16th centuries. This Gothic-style city gate features twin spires and a brick archway, giving it the appearance of a small castle. It is the only remaining entrance from the old city wall and offers stunning views of the surrounding canals.
name: Oostpoort

excerpt: Restored 17th-century hall with portrait paintings from the period & a medieval Gothic belfry tower.
detail_description: The Stadhuis Delft, also known as the City Hall of Delft, is a beautifully restored 17th-century hall that showcases portrait paintings from that era and features a medieval Gothic belfry tower. This grand building, constructed between 1618 and 1620, served as the seat of Delft's municipal government and remains a significant symbol of the city's rich history and communal pride.
name: Stadhuis Delft

excerpt: Antique paintings, porcelain & furniture displayed in the former home of the namesake artist.
detail_description: Nestled in the historic Corn Market (Koornmarkt) area, Museum Paul Tetar van Elven is a captivating attraction showcasing an impressive collection of antique paintings, porcelain, and furniture within the former home of the renowned 19th-century Dutch painter and teacher.
name: Museum Paul Tétar van Elven

detail_description: Nestled just a short stroll from the heart of Delft, the TU Science Center serves as an engaging hub for curious minds of all ages. This vibrant destination combines education with entertainment, featuring interactive exhibits that delve into technology and engineering. Visitors can explore fascinating machines and partake in hands-on experiments that spark creativity and innovation. Sponsored by TU Delft, this center not only showcases groundbreaking research but also offers a playful environment where both children and adults can learn through play.
name: TU Science Center

detail_description: Markt, located in Delft, serves as the central square and a perfect launchpad for discovering the city. The Delft City Hall and the Nieuwe Kerk stand on opposite sides of the square, with numerous bars, cafes, souvenir shops, and pottery outlets in between. This bustling area offers a variety of options for visitors to enjoy while taking in views of the surrounding square.
name: Markt

detail_description: New Life International Church is located in a vibrant area with a Renaissance era town hall and the Nieuwe Kerk (New Church) nearby. The spacious open square between these landmarks is filled with shops and restaurants, making it a popular spot for locals to gather. On sunny days, people can be seen enjoying their lunch beneath the ringing bell towers that chime every quarter of the hour.
name: New Life International Church

detail_description: Kek - De koffiebar van Delft offers a delightful and unique selection of drinks and sandwiches, including special coffee options like salted caramel latte. The menu features a variety of delicious cakes and breakfast choices such as homemade granola with seasonal fruit, chia seeds, and pure chocolate. Vegan guests can enjoy gluten- and sugar-free SUE pastries in various flavors. The coffee is made using a house blend from Giraffe Coffee, ensuring the finest quality.
name: Kek - De koffiebar van Delft

detail_description: Delft's train station is a crucial hub for tourism, despite being connected to the national railway network by only two lines. The station hall is spacious and elegant, also serving as the entrance to Delft city hall. Conveniently located bus and tram stations are just outside. The town itself is known for its iconic blue & white porcelain pottery and artwork, with historic buildings and a relaxed atmosphere adding to its charm.
name: Delft

detail_description: Prinsenhof, located in the old city center of Delft, is a must-visit destination with its authentic castle and classical gardens. This historical site holds significance as the place where William of Orange was assassinated in 1584, with visible bullet holes still present. The museum offers an interesting insight into Dutch history and is considered mandatory reading for every Dutch person.
name: Prinsenhof

excerpt: Cross-shaped Protestant place of worship, built from 1393 to 1655, with a crypt holding royal tombs.
detail_description: Nieuwe Church, located in Delft, is a stunning Protestant place of worship constructed in the shape of a cross. It was built over several centuries and features a crypt that houses royal tombs, including that of William of Orange. The church's 109-meter tower offers breathtaking panoramic views but is not accessible to children under five due to its 376 narrow, spiraling steps.
name: Nieuwe Church

excerpt: Botanical garden run by University of Delft, with arboretum, tropical greenhouse & flower gardens.
detail_description: TU Delft Hortus Botanicus, operated by the University of Delft, is a delightful botanical garden featuring an arboretum, tropical greenhouse, and flower gardens. It offers a diverse living collection of trees categorized into different types, making it an ideal destination for family outings or educational activities. Visitors can explore a wide variety of plants including rare species and perennial trees in addition to several greenhouses showcasing unique plant varieties.
name: TU Delft Hortus Botanicus

detail_description: Delftse Hout offers a perfect outdoor experience with its camping facilities and accommodation options. Whether you prefer traditional tent camping or parking your camper, this little forest retreat has got you covered. For those seeking a touch of luxury, there are glamorous camping choices such as lofts, chalets, and even a grass roof bungalow available for an overnight stay.
name: Delftse Hout

detail_description: Experience the charm of Delft with a boat trip through its extensive network of canals. While the glass roof may limit some views, the 45-minute journey offers an insightful tour led by a knowledgeable guide who shares captivating stories about the city's history. Despite slightly uncomfortable seating, this excursion provides a unique perspective on Delft's picturesque scenery and is highly recommended for visitors to the area.
name: Boat Trip Delft

detail_description: De Waag, located in the heart of Delft at Markt Square, has a rich historical significance dating back to 1246 when it was known as Marktveld. This iconic location has been hosting a weekly market on Thursdays for centuries and continues to do so today. The majestic Dutch cafe offers a unique dining experience with its modern take on local cuisine, such as the loin of pork with gingerbread crunch.
name: De Waag

detail_description: Bierhuis De Klomp is a must-visit for beer enthusiasts in Delft, known as the oldest bar in the city with origins dating back to the 17th century. The cozy and authentic atmosphere of this historic establishment offers a selection of 80 different beers, including local brews and international classics. Despite its small exterior, the interior is surprisingly spacious, divided into unique areas such as the Voorheis where locals often gather.
name: Bierhuis De Klomp

detail_description: The Maria van Jessekerk, a Gothic Revival Roman Catholic parish church in Delft, South Holland, is a striking architectural marvel completed in 1882. Its two towers rise above the city's skyline and boast designs reminiscent of the New Church and Old Church. The interior underwent a transformation in 1905 with vibrant colorful paint and finely executed murals depicting over 100 figures. Originally dedicated to Saint Joseph, it was rededicated to Maria van Jesse in 1971.
name: Maria van Jessekerk

detail_description: The cultural center Prinsenkwartier offers a good location, great service and great drinks and cakes.
name: Prinsenkwartier

detail_description: Theater de Veste is a vibrant cultural hub that welcomes visitors with its bright, cheerful ambiance and an array of performances. This cozy venue hosts a diverse lineup of shows, from dance and music to acrobatics and live theater, ensuring there's something for everyone. Conveniently located near public transport and parking facilities, it’s easily accessible for all. Upon entering Theater de Veste, guests are greeted by a spacious foyer complete with a bar where friendly staff members are always ready to assist.
name: Theater de Veste

detail_description: Stads-Koffyhuis, located at Oude Delft 133 in Delft, Netherlands, may appear as a small coffee house from the outside but is actually a modern and spacious restaurant offering top-quality international dishes. The menu features high-quality classic dishes served in a cozy atmosphere. This establishment also offers delightful high tea experiences and a variety of breakfast options until 11:30 am.
name: Stads-Koffyhuis

detail_description: Hummus Delft offers a selection of four types of hummus served with homemade pitas made from flour ground in the Delft mill. Additionally, guests can opt for dips like baba ganoush or feta, accompanied by sides such as sweet potato fries and foul mudammes. The menu also features various salads and specials like Shakshuka. This restaurant is known for its delicious fresh hummus and other Middle Eastern dishes.
name: Hummus Delft

detail_description: When exploring Delft, make sure to stop by Terre des Hommes Winkel, a charming charity shop that offers a delightful selection of branded clothing in excellent condition and lovely home decor items (though no furniture). This small yet inviting store is known for its friendly atmosphere and helpful staff, making your shopping experience enjoyable. Visitors often praise the quality of the merchandise and appreciate the good cause behind their purchases.
name: Terre des Hommes winkel

detail_description: If you're on the hunt for unique treasures, de Flinstones is a must-visit spot, even if it was closed during my visit. This charming thrift store offers an eclectic mix of second-hand goods that can make any bargain hunter's heart race. Picture a mini warehouse brimming with items—it's like stepping into a treasure trove where you might just stumble upon that perfect find! The atmosphere is delightfully chaotic, filled with everything from furniture to quirky knick-knacks.
name: de Flinstones

detail_description: Galerie 'Uit De Kunst' is a unique and charming place located in the picturesque Oude Delft since 1982. It offers a delightful combination of a gallery showcasing beautiful handmade clothing and art, along with a cozy café where visitors can relax with a cup of coffee, homemade treats, and delicious lunch options.
name: Galerie 'Uit De Kunst'

excerpt: Showroom producing & selling the classic, hand painted local pottery brand, plus artisan workshops.
name: Delft Pottery De Delftse Pauw

detail_description: De Gist is a trendy bar known for serving the best beers in town and delicious snacks, making it a great spot for business meetings or casual hangouts. It offers a wide selection of beers on tap and serves breakfast, lunch, and dinner. The cozy atmosphere extends from an open cafe area to secluded rooms with beautiful canal views. Visitors praise the food options, particularly the meat dishes like chicken, ribs, and steak, as well as the must-try chips.
name: De Gist

detail_description: Bij Best is a great place to get a quick lunch or breakfast. The food is always fresh and the service is friendly and fast. They have lots of options for both sweet and savory dishes, so there's something for everyone. If you're looking for a local spot to enjoy some good food, Bij Best should definitely be your go-to!
name: Bij Best. Breakfast, Lunch & Coffee

excerpt: Casual restaurant with wooden furniture serving Dutch & European cafe fare alongside beer & coffee.
detail_description: Located in the heart of Delft, 't Postkantoor is a casual restaurant housed in a historic building that used to be the city's post office from 1890 to 2005. The spacious interior features warm and inviting decor with wooden furniture, cozy seating areas, and an open fireplace.
name: 't Postkantoor

detail_description: Belgian Beer Cafe Belvédère is a popular spot located on the corner of Beestenmarkt in the Netherlands. It offers a wide selection of over 15 Belgian beers on tap and delicious food, making it an ideal place for both large and small gatherings with friends. The cafe provides a European outdoor cafe experience, especially enjoyable on warm sunny days when locals frequent the area.
name: Belgian Beer Cafe Belvédère

detail_description: LOT. Coffee Boutique is a specialty coffee bar located on a quaint street, offering a minimalist interior and the relaxing rhythms of lo-fi music. The café features a striking pink Victoria Arduino coffee machine as its centerpiece, brewing Dublin-sourced beans with care. In addition to regular coffee options, LOT offers special brews like flash or cold batch brew. It's also known for its delectable pastries and biscuits, making it an ideal spot for those with a sweet tooth.
name: LOT. coffee boutique

detail_description: The Lambert van Meerten Museum in Delft is a captivating destination for those interested in Dutch history and culture. This unique museum, housed in a grand residence, showcases an impressive collection of building fragments, Delft pottery, and furniture from the Dutch Golden Age. Visitors are encouraged to engage with the exhibits by touching items and exploring various rooms, creating an immersive experience that feels like stepping back in time. The friendly staff enhances the visit, offering assistance as you wander through this historical treasure trove.
name: Lambert van Meerten Museum

detail_description: TU Delft Library is a remarkable piece of modern architecture located at Delft University of Technology in the Netherlands. The building's unique design includes a large cone supporting a grass-covered roof, creating a harmonious blend with the surrounding landscape. It was one of the first upgrades to the campus and is considered an impressive and imaginative structure that seems built into the earth. Inside, it offers plenty of spaces for studying or discussions, as well as a cafe where visitors can enjoy their food.
name: TU Delft Library

detail_description: Rietveld Theater is a charming venue that offers a variety of entertainment options for visitors. It hosts Dans & Grietje kids disco during school holidays, complete with craft activities and interactive workshops like drumming or dancing. The theater also presents diverse performances including Cabaret, Jazz, Classical music, and children's shows. Visitors praise the friendly atmosphere and the opportunity to enjoy a drink while watching the shows.
name: Rietveld Theater

excerpt: Relaxed rooms in a chic hotel offering a cozy guest lounge, a garden & complimentary Wi-Fi.
detail_description: Casa Julia is a charming boutique hotel located in the heart of Delft, offering relaxed and cozy rooms with bright and fresh interiors. The hotel provides a peaceful atmosphere with calming coastal colors that evoke a gentle sea breeze. Guests can enjoy breakfast in bed and take advantage of the bike rental service to explore the city along the canals. The hotel also offers amenities such as complimentary Wi-Fi, a guest lounge, a garden, and eco-certified facilities.
name: Casa Julia

excerpt: Laid-back quarters, some inside wooden trailers, plus complimentary breakfast, a bar & a courtyard.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Delft, Hotel de Emauspoort offers a delightful blend of comfort and charm that feels just like home. This unique establishment, which once served as a sweet shop in the 1920s, has been welcoming travelers since 1995. Guests can choose from bright, individually decorated rooms or opt for an unforgettable experience in one of the cozy gypsy caravans located in the picturesque courtyard.
name: de Emauspoort 'Just like home'

excerpt: Low-key rooms in a laid-back property featuring canal views & complimentary Wi-Fi.
detail_description: Hotel Grand Canal in Delft offers a laid-back stay with canal views and complimentary Wi-Fi. The 3-star property is conveniently located near attractions like Delft Town Hall and Oude Kerk, making it an ideal base for exploring the city. Guests can enjoy amenities such as room service, a restaurant, bar, and rooms with kitchenettes. The hotel's unique Venetian-style building was once a prison and now offers cozy accommodations within walking distance of popular sights.
name: Hotel Grand Canal

detail_description: PLECK Conceptstore Delft is a charming and cozy cafe in Delft, offering a relaxed atmosphere with friendly staff. It stands out for its unique concept of being a WiFi-free zone and providing conversation starters instead. The shop also features a delightful concept store section to browse through. Visitors can enjoy excellent coffee, delicious treats, and the option to work or relax in the beautifully designed seating area at the back of the store.
name: PLECK Conceptstore Delft - Shop, Coffee, Create

detail_description: Nestled a bit outside the bustling center, Leuke Boel is a delightful treasure trove for those seeking unique finds beyond just clothing. This charming shop specializes in furniture and various intriguing items, all presented in an organized and inviting atmosphere that feels refreshingly clutter-free. The friendly owners create a lively environment, making your shopping experience enjoyable as they assist you in discovering hidden gems.
name: Leuke Boel

detail_description: When visiting Delft, make sure to take a leisurely walk through the city center to admire the charming traditional architecture. The streets of Voldersgracht, Oude Delft, and Oosteinde offer picturesque views that capture the essence of Dutch heritage. For an authentic Dutch experience, consider visiting Molen de Roos (Rose Windmill), which is still in operation and conveniently located within a 10-minute walk from Markt Square.
name: Oude Delft

detail_description: Hofje van Pauw is a charming historical site in Delft, built in 1707 as per the wishes of Elisabeth Pauw, daughter of a mayor of Delft. It comprises eight houses and is part of a group that includes Hofje van Gratie, Hofje van Almonde, and Klaauwshofje.
name: Hofje van Pauw
